#: ../../development/errorhandling.rst:10
msgid ""
"PDAL typically throws a ``std::runtime_error`` for error conditions that "
"is catchable as ``pdal::pdal_error``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../development/errorhandling.rst:14
msgid "PDAL Position on (Non)conformance"
msgstr ""

#: ../../development/errorhandling.rst:16
msgid ""
"PDAL proudly and unabashedly supports formal standards/specifications for"
" file formats.  We recognize, however, that in some cases files will not "
"follow a given standard precisely, due to an unclear spec or simply out "
"of carelessness."
msgstr ""

#: ../../development/errorhandling.rst:21
msgid "When reading files that are not formatted correctly:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../development/errorhandling.rst:23
msgid ""
"PDAL may try to compensate for the error.  This is typically done when as"
" a practical matter the market needs support for well-known or pervasive,"
" but nonetheless \"broken\", upstream implementations."
msgstr ""

#: ../../development/errorhandling.rst:27
msgid ""
"PDAL may explicitly reject such files.  This is typically done where we "
"do not wish to continue to promote or support mistakes that should be "
"fixed upstream."
msgstr ""

#: ../../development/errorhandling.rst:31
msgid ""
"PDAL will strive to write correctly formatted files.  In some cases, "
"however, PDAL may choose to offer as an option the ability to break the "
"standard if, as a practical matter, doing so would significantly aid the "
"market.  Such an option would never be the default behavior, however."
msgstr ""

#: ../../development/errorhandling.rst:36
msgid ""
"For files that are conformant but which lie, such as the extents in the "
"header being wrong, we will generally offer both the ability to propagate"
" the \"wrong\" information and the ability to helpfully correct it on the"
" fly; the latter is generally our default position."
msgstr ""

